          // TL;DR
          .card.border-0.bg-light.p-4.mb-4
            h5.fw-bold TL;DR / Key Takeaways
            ul.mb-0
              li 
                strong Primary Indicator:
                |  An inability to limit or stop drinking once you start is a core symptom of Alcohol Use Disorder (AUD).
              li 
                strong Social Consequences:
                |  If your drinking affects your job, relationships, or health, it's a sign that needs attention.
              li 
                strong Physical Signs:
                |  Tolerance (needing more to feel the effect) and withdrawal (shaking, anxiety) are advanced red flags.
              li 
                strong The Question:
                |  Most social drinkers don't spend time wondering if they are alcoholic. Asking the question is often the first sign.

          // Quick Definition (Featured Snippet)
          h2.mt-2 Quick Definition
          p.lead
             strong Alcohol Use Disorder (AUD) 
             |  is a chronic relapsing brain disorder characterized by an impaired ability to stop or control alcohol use despite adverse social, occupational, or health consequences. It ranges from mild to severe and is a clinical diagnosis that replaces the informal term "alcoholism."

          .mb-5.p-4.bg-light.rounded
            h4.h5 Table of Contents
            ul.list-unstyled.mb-0
