          hr.my-5

          // Section 1
          h2#why-it-matters
            i.bi.bi-info-circle.text-primary.me-2
            | Why Asking "Am I an Alcoholic?" Matters
          
          p For many, the word "alcoholic" carries a heavy weight of stigma—a vision of someone who has lost everything and is drinking from a paper bag on a park bench. But in the modern recovery world, we recognize that **Alcohol Use Disorder (AUD)** affects people in every tax bracket, profession, and neighborhood in Spokane.
          p Identifying these signs isn't about labeling yourself for shame; it's about gaining the clarity needed to reclaim your life before the consequences become permanent.

          h2#15-signs.mt-5
            i.bi.bi-exclamation-triangle.text-primary.me-2
            | 15 Honest Signs You Shouldn't Ignore
          
          .mb-4
            h3 1. You can’t stop once you start
            p You tell yourself you'll only have two drinks, but you end up having six or more. This lack of a "stop switch" is a neurological hallmark of AUD.
            
            h3 2. You’ve tried to quit and failed
            p You make "deals" with yourself, like only drinking on weekends or never drinking before 5 PM, but you find yourself breaking these rules repeatedly.
            
            h3 3. You spend a lot of time drinking or recovering
            p Between the time spent obtaining alcohol, the act of drinking, and the "hangover days" spent recovering, alcohol consumes a significant portion of your week.
            
            h3 4. Your tolerance has increased significantly
            p It takes much more alcohol to reach the same level of relaxation or "buzz" than it used to. This is a sign that your brain chemistry is adapting to the substance.
            
            h3 5. You have cravings or a "mental obsession"
            p You find yourself thinking about your next drink at work, during lunch, or while driving home. It feels like an itch you have to scratch.
            
            h3 6. You’re neglecting responsibilities
            p Missing work, being late for school, or failing to take care of household chores because you’re either drinking or hungover.
            
            h3 7. You drink in dangerous situations
            p This includes drinking and driving, or drinking while operating machinery or caring for children, despite knowing the risks.
            
            h3 8. You’ve given up things you love
            p You no longer participate in hobbies, sports, or social activities you once enjoyed because they interfere with your drinking schedule.
            
            h3 9. You continue to drink despite health problems
            p Even after a doctor warns you about liver enzymes, high blood pressure, or stomach issues, you find it impossible to stop.
            
            h3 10. You drink alone or in secret
            p You hide bottles or finish your drink before meeting friends so they don't see how much you're actually consuming.
            
            h3 11. You use alcohol as your only coping mechanism
            p Whether you’re stressed, happy, sad, or bored, alcohol is the only tool in your kit for handling emotions.
            
            h3 12. You have memory blackouts
            p You wake up unable to remember parts of the previous night, even if you seemed "fine" to those around you.
            
            h3 13. Your relationships are strained
            p Friends or family members have expressed concern about your drinking, leading to arguments or your withdrawal from those relationships.
            
            h3 14. You feel shaky or anxious when you don't drink
            p These are early signs of physical withdrawal. If you need a "hair of the dog" to stop the shakes in the morning, your body has become dependent.
            
            h3 15. You’re reading this article
            p **Expert Note:** Social drinkers don't usually Google "signs of alcoholism." If you are seeking answers, your intuition is already signaling that something is wrong.

          h2#comparison.mt-5
            i.bi.bi-table.text-primary.me-2
            | Social Drinking vs. Problem Drinking
          
          p It can be hard to tell the difference if everyone in your social circle drinks heavily. Here is a comparison to help clarify.

          .table-responsive.mt-4
            table.table.table-bordered.bg-white
              thead.bg-light
                tr
                  th Feature
                  th Social Drinking
                  th Problem Drinking (AUD)
              tbody
                tr
                  td **Intent**
                  td To enhance an experience.
                  td To change how you feel or escape.
                tr
                  td **Ability to Stop**
                  td Can easily stop after one or two.
                  td Difficulty stopping once started.
                tr
                  td **Control**
                  td Drinking is a choice, not a need.
                  td Drinking feels like a compulsion.
                tr
                  td **Consequences**
                  td Rarely causes social or legal issues.
                  td Continued use despite recurring problems.
                tr
                  td **Health**
                  td Minimal impact on daily function.
                  td Can lead to withdrawal, tolerance, and organ damage.

          h2#process.mt-5
            i.bi.bi-journal-check.text-primary.me-2
            | The Step-by-Step Path to Recovery
          
          p If some of these signs resonate with you, here is how you can begin your journey toward sobriety in Spokane.

          h3 Step 1: Honest Self-Assessment
          p Take a day to track your drinking without judgment. Write down how much and why you drank.
          p 
            strong Pro Tip:
            |  Download a recovery tracking app to see patterns you might be missing.
          p 
            strong Common Pitfall:
            |  Underestimating the amount. Be brutally honest with yourself.

          h3 Step 2: Consult a Professional
          p Talk to your primary care doctor about your drinking. They can provide a medical diagnosis and check your physical health.
          p 
            strong Pro Tip:
            |  If you live in Spokane, the [Spokane Valley Recovery Resources](/spokane-valley-recovery-resources.html) page lists local clinics.

          h3 Step 3: Explore Support Groups
          p Groups like Alcoholics Anonymous (AA) or SMART Recovery offer immediate community.
          p 
            strong Pro Tip:
            |  Check out our guide on [AA & NA Meetings in Spokane](/blog/aa-na-meetings-spokane.html) to find a meeting today.

          h3 Step 4: Consider Professional Treatment
          p If you find you cannot stop on your own, inpatient or outpatient treatment may be necessary.
          p 
            strong Pro Tip:
            |  Read about [Inpatient vs. Outpatient Rehab](/blog/inpatient-vs-outpatient-rehab-spokane.html) to see which fits your life.

          hr.my-5

          // Common Mistakes
          h2#mistakes.mt-5
            i.bi.bi-x-octagon-fill.text-danger.me-2
            | Common Mistakes in Early Assessment
          
          ol.mt-4
            li.mb-3
              strong Mistake: Comparing yourself to "worse" alcoholics.
              br
              strong Fix:
              |  Don't wait until you've lost your house or job to seek help. Recovery is easier when you still have a foundation.
            li.mb-3
              strong Mistake: Trying to "white knuckle" a detox.
              br
              strong Fix:
              |  Alcohol withdrawal can be fatal. If you drink daily, seek professional medical detox.
            li.mb-3
              strong Mistake: Thinking a "break" will fix it.
              br
              strong Fix:
              |  "Dry January" is great, but for those with AUD, it usually leads back to heavy drinking once the month ends. Look for long-term lifestyle changes.

